WEBVTT

00:01.837 --> 00:05.643
to Hispanic employees, and did this treatment 
change over time? Well, actually,

00:07.346 --> 00:20.746
at the onset, let's talk about the dining hall, for 
instance. Way back there, the only thing they

00:22.990 --> 00:29.700
hired were people from Mexico, for some reason or 
another, because they were considered good

00:30.119 --> 00:37.088
cooks, I guess, and

00:30.119 --> 00:37.088
good workers. So you're saying the dining hall was 
mostly spent? Yeah, I would say that 100% were

00:42.575 --> 00:47.521
people from Mexico. And they did a heck of a good 
job, and they took good care of the students. They

00:53.609 --> 00:55.131
were also cooks. you know, salad people, which I 
don't know what you call that, but they made salads

00:55.718 --> 01:02.826
for people. And they were also people who

01:02.906 --> 01:17.062
took up, well, cleaned the mess afterwards, you 
know, they were KP people, bus boys and what have

01:02.906 --> 01:17.062
you. And... What about managing the place? The 
manager also was from Mexico, by the name of Juan

01:26.043 --> 01:28.086
Peña, I think his name was. Peña, Juan Peña. He was 
also. But then something happened. The state

01:33.352 --> 01:44.766
legislature passed a law that non-citizens could 
not work in a state-owned institution or

01:33.352 --> 01:44.766
state-operated institution. So abruptly, they 
were all let out. And so then they hired an American

01:55.017 --> 02:04.088
American citizens, and they hired Hispanics and 
blacks and Anglos and everything else. But I mean,

02:05.310 --> 02:11.037
everybody was treated well there. As far as the 
overall campus is concerned, there weren't too

02:11.057 --> 02:18.006
many opportunities for Hispanics to work on the 
campus. I don't know why.

02:23.384 --> 02:30.275
Even right now, the percentage of Hispanic 
workers is very, very low. I mean, you've hardly

02:30.555 --> 02:33.379
seen them. And I know that a lot of them are 
qualified. And even when I was there, when I was

02:38.547 --> 02:52.108
there at operation manager, I hired Hispanics to 
work as students mostly.

02:52.544 --> 02:53.465
office workers. I had several Hispanic office 
workers. And you could see quite a few office

02:57.590 --> 03:02.216
workers of Hispanic origin also on the campus. But 
as far as a male

03:02.957 --> 03:11.868
worker is concerned, Hispanic worker, you hardly 
see them on the campus. This is one thing I don't

03:11.888 --> 03:13.530
understand. And I think that exists now. Other 
than student Hispanics, Hispanic Male workers

03:21.603 --> 03:25.488
are very scarce on the campus. I noticed that. I was 
there 52 years. And during all those years, it

03:29.314 --> 03:32.679
never did improve, as far as I'm concerned. 
Really? Never did. I don't know why. I don't

03:36.904 --> 03:40.049
understand it, because they are good workers. Did 
you ever work with any other Spanx? Hardly ever, I

03:42.212 --> 03:44.455
assume? What do you mean, did I work with them? In 
your job. Did I work some of them? Work with them.

03:49.775 --> 03:52.999
Yeah, I had real good workers. Yeah, I had Isidro 
Lopez, who worked with me for years. Actually, he

04:00.469 --> 04:07.177
was a foreman under me, and he did a good job. Very 
dedicated. I mean, he'd be the first set and the

04:08.299 --> 04:10.982
last leave. If you needed him on a Saturday or 
Sunday, he was there, no question. And I'm sure

04:16.474 --> 04:24.204
that your Uncle Paul, who also was foreman at the 
dining hall, he can tell you about the Hispanic

04:16.474 --> 04:24.204
workers. But he would have trouble with these, you 
know, with some of these other workers of other

04:24.945 --> 04:31.414
nationalities who just didn't. And you can see it 
now. You take, right now, your hardworking people

04:33.337 --> 04:41.307
or your people from Mexico and your Hispanic 
people, they're working. But I have people here

04:42.113 --> 04:48.981
somehow, I don't know what it is, we just don't want 
to work anymore. First thing they want to know is

04:50.964 --> 05:05.301
how much you're going to pay them, and of course 
that's a good thing, but how many breaks you get

04:50.964 --> 05:05.301
during the day and how long you break, stuff like 
that. Whereas you, one of these Mexican workers,

05:09.535 --> 05:10.456
They'll work right now. They don't ask those kind 
of questions. But getting back to your original

05:12.679 --> 05:25.757
question about how to, I think your question was, 
how did A&M react to the Hispanic workers or

05:12.679 --> 05:25.757
something like that? How did they treat them? Was 
it equal treatment for them? Well, there were

05:28.200 --> 05:33.687
some, of course, there's pros and cons here. Where 
I stood, I thought some were treated unjustly. But

05:38.948 --> 05:44.093
the overall administrator did not think so. They 
had some other overrulia, and that was it. But you

05:51.160 --> 05:58.807
hardly see any Hispanic foreman anywhere in 
charge of anything.

06:01.450 --> 06:06.795
And there's never been a large influx of expanding 
workers that ain't them, male that is. And I doubt

06:11.479 --> 06:14.862
if there are too many female. Whether that's 
because there's not enough skill amongst them,

06:14.882 --> 06:31.059
because some of these jobs do require skill, like 
they need carpenters, painters, electricians,

06:14.882 --> 06:31.059
and air conditioned people, and they're all 
Anglos. But even today, would you say that at

06:32.060 --> 06:35.483
managerial levels, It hasn't really changed 
much. There really aren't many Hispanics at all.

06:39.555 --> 06:41.297
No, it has not changed much at all. I can tell you 
that right now. It has not changed. Well, how did

06:44.962 --> 06:52.492
your coworkers, non-Hispanic coworkers, 
respond to you or to other Hispanics working with

06:44.962 --> 06:52.492
them? Was there a problem there? Was that an equal 
footing, I would say? You're asking how did I get

06:58.461 --> 07:00.964
along with my... Anglo co-workers? Yes. Well, I 
got along fine with them. Actually, when you come

07:07.886 --> 07:24.271
right down to it, you could call the whole system 
co-workers, that is the wage people, that is the

07:07.886 --> 07:24.271
so-called non-faculty people, because y'all 
work together for the university. And in my

07:25.312 --> 07:29.398
capacity, since chemistry was the largest 
department, largest department on campus, we

07:30.593 --> 07:41.126
required more of the physical plant services than 
any other department. And as a result, I got to see

07:42.628 --> 07:54.162
those people more and I had a chance to work with 
them and I found that they were very good to me. And I

07:54.282 --> 07:57.646
tried to be as equal as them, be the same as them. We 
worked together. And even now, when I'm retired,

07:59.973 --> 08:04.057
and I'm retired, I meet them on the street. Boy, 
they don't hesitate to go and shake my hand. We talk

08:07.421 --> 08:08.642
about it all the time. So they actually got along 
fine. So I got along with them all right. Being

08:16.410 --> 08:20.694
Hispanic, it seemed to me that they have that same 
attitude toward other Hispanics. So it might be

08:20.714 --> 08:24.698
that maybe, I don't know what it is. I just can't put 
my finger on it, why the Hispanics are not being

08:24.718 --> 08:29.203
hired more over there. Let me ask you about, I know 
you were involved on the grievances committee.

08:34.429 --> 08:38.392
Can you tell me in what capacity you served the 
grievances committee? And if there were any

08:38.432 --> 08:48.561
special incidences that have an impact on 
employees at Texas A&M that you feel you can

08:38.432 --> 08:48.561
comment on because of that experience? Well, the 
problem here is that I did not deal with Hispanics

08:48.701 --> 08:57.589
on this. But I was the only Hispanic. on this 
so-called panel. And instead of taking the

09:04.135 --> 09:12.522
grievance, a person taking his grievances to 
court, he would take it to this panel. And this

09:12.683 --> 09:17.327
panel, from this panel, he could pick out someone 
to defend him. And then the other people that were

09:18.848 --> 09:24.213
against him could pick out someone to defend them. 
And then from the panel, they had a group that would

09:25.054 --> 09:30.139
act as judge and jury. And so they'd hear us. And the 
university would accept that recommendation.

09:35.638 --> 09:37.080
And to me, it was fair. It was fair. I think it was 
real fair. Not all that. The guy who

09:41.025 --> 09:51.298
felt that he was done an injustice could go out and 
get a lawyer instead of getting one of us. And I saw

09:51.979 --> 09:55.643
that only at one time, that's all. And to me, it was 
effective in that actually there was one incident

09:59.988 --> 10:28.257
where one fellow was more or less fired and he felt 
that they did it just when he got hurt on the job and

09:59.988 --> 10:28.257
the hospital was pretty expensive so I 
represented him and as a result of

09:59.988 --> 10:28.257
the hearing and And the discussion that went on, 
actually

10:29.114 --> 10:37.868
he was reinstated and they paid for the 
hospitalization. And if I'm thinking right, I

10:38.949 --> 10:42.034
think he's still there. But they had let him go. 
They had let him go. He was fired, period. And this

10:47.142 --> 10:49.206
is what this grievance was all about. But I never 
did. Since there's not too many Hispanics, well,

10:51.490 --> 10:55.856
no problem with none there, hardly. Very few at 
that time. Now, I've been gone four years. Now,

10:59.741 --> 11:01.904
they might have had a large group there, but I doubt 
it. I don't think so. Because I don't see them, and I

11:03.005 --> 11:09.313
don't hear anybody that I know tell me they work at 
A&M except one or two, and that's it. The same one or

11:09.553 --> 11:12.317
two that have been there 20 years, they're the same 
ones there now. Something else I'd like you to

11:12.955 --> 11:15.438
comment on along those lines. You were 
instrumental in the first affirmative action

11:15.518 --> 11:19.463
program at Texas A&M. Can you tell me how you got 
that going and what exactly was entailed, what it

11:20.144 --> 11:24.910
produced? Well, actually, I got this letter from 
President Runner

11:24.950 --> 11:42.152
asking me if I would serve with this committee of 
four to come up with an affirmative action program

11:24.950 --> 11:42.152
for the university since just about every other 
university on the campus, I mean the state of Texas

11:42.385 --> 11:48.111
had one except us. When was this? Peter had been, oh 
God, maybe ten years ago, I guess, that's a good

11:50.033 --> 11:56.119
rough guess. That's when it was, Pratt & Rudder was 
still, no, no, it wasn't Pratt & Rudder.

12:01.225 --> 12:02.106
Vanderbilt? No, no, Williamson. Okay. Chained 
after it was Pratt & Williamson, that's right,

12:05.269 --> 12:09.253
right after, yeah. So that had been about 10 years 
ago. And so I thought I'd be honored to serve on it.

12:17.353 --> 12:32.594
And so the purpose of that was to make sure that the

12:17.353 --> 12:32.594
university would hire a fair percentage of Anglos 
and Blacks. And that the university would make a

12:33.716 --> 12:39.223
strong effort to hire Spanish and Blacks. And it 
was an intricate thing to deal with. And I don't

12:48.092 --> 12:57.743
know whether it's had any impact on hiring 
Hispanics, because I thought for sure that it

12:48.092 --> 12:57.743
would. But as far as I know, I don't think so. But the 
thing is that this thing also applied for the

13:02.629 --> 13:05.873
faculty. And of course, they hired quite a few 
Hispanic faculty. And that's what I'm saying. If

13:11.466 --> 13:22.580
the Hispanic has some sort of preparation or some 
sort of an academic background, I think he can be

13:11.466 --> 13:22.580
hired. But sometimes I wonder whether the 
applicants that are turned down, whether they're

13:22.600 --> 13:31.111
qualified or not to accept this particular job 
they want. And I think the affirmative action is a

13:32.313 --> 13:37.780
good thing to have. if they go ahead and carry it out 
like it's supposed to, or if they were to implement

13:38.418 --> 13:48.587
it like it should be, but I don't think they are. 
Actually, one of the affirmative action officers

13:48.787 --> 14:06.163
that left about four or five years ago told me that 
she left because the university was not strong on

13:48.787 --> 14:06.163
implementing the affirmative action. you know uh 
whatever affirmative action uh program and uh so i

14:06.515 --> 14:31.729
really can't tell you whether it's done any good or 
not peter uh i doubt if it has of course uh president

14:06.515 --> 14:31.729
reagan didn't want that in the country i don't 
think i think he wanted to get rid of it but they

