still have it at nm And according to newspapers, 
A&M is doing all they can to recruit minorities,

14:32.823 --> 14:42.492
not only in school, but also in jobs. And I don't 
know just how well they've done. I don't know. Let

14:50.380 --> 14:54.844
me change gears once again and ask you about 
something that's a little more recent. The last 10

14:56.806 --> 15:01.210
or 15 years has seen sort of a new wave of 
immigration from Mexico. How do you think this has

15:01.527 --> 15:04.110
affected the Hispanic community in Bryan? Have 
these people generally been accepted? Is there a

15:07.855 --> 15:10.277
pro and con to this issue? What's your response? 
Explain that again, Peter. I kind of see what it is.

15:15.023 --> 15:16.885
You're talking about people from Mexico now, 
right? Right. The immigrants, the aliens coming

15:17.426 --> 15:18.928
over. How has that affected this community? Okay, 
you're talking about the working people. You're

15:23.213 --> 15:26.276
not talking about... Well, I don't think there's 
too many of the other. Okay, all right. Actually,

15:28.159 --> 15:29.340
Pete... Peter, I think it's helped the community. 
And I think that

15:32.430 --> 15:50.583
people, leading citizens of the community think 
that without these people, they couldn't have

15:32.430 --> 15:50.583
accomplished what they have thus far, like for 
instance, roadworks. Because of the labor force.

15:51.584 --> 15:53.067
The labor force. At A&M, you take at A&M, all this 
big building program they've got going there. If

15:58.553 --> 16:07.443
you go there, you'll notice that so many of them, 
the big majority of them, that are doing the hard

15:58.553 --> 16:07.443
work and are doing the heavy semen work are 
Hispanics. And they're the ones that are doing a

16:08.124 --> 16:16.412
lot of the so-called bricklaying, doing a lot of 
semen work, this fine semen work. A lot of them are

16:16.432 --> 16:18.715
doing this fine hard work. And you can see that in 
Brian, too. In Brian, you take younger brothers

16:20.357 --> 16:22.699
who who is one of the largest road contractors 
around here,

16:23.573 --> 16:38.241
he'll tell you right now that without those 
people, he couldn't keep up with his deadline. He

16:38.262 --> 16:40.466
couldn't meet his deadline. And if you drive any 
place while they're doing this, you'll find that

16:40.486 --> 16:46.257
they are that there's a lot of these people from 
Mexico that are there doing this hard work. A lot of

16:52.168 --> 16:55.532
these people do a lot of work for the city of Bryan. 
The city of Bryan can't find American citizens to

16:56.353 --> 17:06.386
do this work, so they have to rely on these amnesty 
people to do that. And they're the one that do your

17:07.187 --> 17:11.032
farm work for you. They're the one that clean your 
cow sheds and your horse sheds. They do a lot of

17:17.236 --> 17:18.217
work. And now, as you know, a lot of our own here, I 
don't think the black community want to do that

17:18.638 --> 17:26.688
work anymore. They figure that you don't see black 
people doing that kind of work no more. They used

17:31.794 --> 17:33.416
to, but not anymore. They don't feel that they 
should. And so if they're going to do it, then your

17:36.660 --> 17:43.328
wage is going to go way up. And these people that are 
working hard, they're working for the way you said

17:43.898 --> 17:51.408
they are now, whatever it is. I get a lot of minimum 
wage at the beginning. Do you think that there's

17:56.355 --> 18:11.215
been any negative response, perhaps in light of 
the fact that some would say this is sort of

17:56.355 --> 18:11.215
bringing a rising Hispanic community a step back? 
It's an added weight. Do you see it in that light?

18:14.088 --> 18:15.830
And that in way to the Hispanic community? Yes. 
Well, I think that

18:17.691 --> 18:31.824
I don't think that the Hispanic community feel 
that these Amnesty workers are taking their jobs

18:17.691 --> 18:31.824
away from them. Because they probably won't do 
that job either because they speak well English,

18:31.844 --> 18:43.234
they speak good English, and they can get better 
jobs working in stores and places like that. To me,

18:43.703 --> 18:57.382
I think it helps because, especially the Hispanic 
business people, because a lot of these people go

18:43.703 --> 18:57.382
to the Hispanic business people because they can 
communicate with them. And the people who are in

18:57.402 --> 19:07.275
some sort of recreation, the Hispanic people, 
these people patronize them because they

18:57.402 --> 19:07.275
commute. No, I don't think so. I think that the 
Hispanic community considers them an advantage.

19:12.931 --> 19:13.532
being here. I know that in the past you've worked 
with naturalization of aliens. Can you tell me

19:20.259 --> 19:21.560
something about that? What exactly was involved? 
Well, actually,

19:22.921 --> 19:39.799
many, when we came back from the war, from 
overseas,

19:22.921 --> 19:39.799
at that time it finally hit me that it was not fair 
that the parents of these boys that went overseas

19:40.960 --> 19:51.955
and fought for this country, and many of them 
didn't even come back, that their parents had no

19:40.960 --> 19:51.955
rights, couldn't even vote. And they've been here 
for 50 years, 20, 40 years, and still didn't have a

19:51.975 --> 19:57.422
right to vote. And actually, those that were real 
poor had not even right for welfare, not even right

19:58.604 --> 20:05.192
for anything. And the only way that they could have 
this right by becoming a citizen. And so we decided

20:14.885 --> 20:19.831
to go ahead and set up schools. We went to the they 
had a lawyer organization here. I forget the name

20:25.699 --> 20:26.881
of it. And we went to them and they got together with 
the American Legion and said they would help us as

20:27.882 --> 20:38.777
far as the lawyers were concerned to write up some 
of the things that they need to know, and the

20:39.280 --> 20:42.906
questions and answers and so forth. Kind of a 
textbook in tablet form. And they wrote this

20:45.912 --> 20:47.555
textbook for us. Because the one from, I got a 
textbook from San Antonio Immigration Service,

20:48.496 --> 20:56.230
from Immigration Services in San Antonio. 
They're very complicated, it's only English. But

20:59.155 --> 21:01.980
they did it in English. But we found a group here 
that would be able to transfer. They translated in

21:05.426 --> 21:07.928
Spanish. So we had both of them. So they had both of 
them. So then we got together. Your uncle Paul and I

21:12.733 --> 21:22.984
got together and studied this thing, I mean, 
extensively until we learned about it ourselves.

21:23.704 --> 21:29.470
And then this information, we started having 
classes and passed it on to them. And they were very

21:30.243 --> 21:31.965
eager to learn. They learned. And not only that, we 
had to go to a lot of trouble to establish a

21:34.228 --> 21:39.735
residence for them. A lot of them came here in 1902 
and couldn't prove it. So we had the right to places

21:45.001 --> 21:49.326
where they worked or take them over there. I mean, 
we made many trips out to Braggers Bottom, Waco, to

21:49.346 --> 21:59.018
San Antonio, to places like that, the way they They 
entered, and people that knew them, and we got

21:59.521 --> 22:04.188
affidavits from these people that they worked 
for. And that's how we did it. And it was a hassle.

22:09.255 --> 22:11.297
But we made them into citizens that way. And we'd 
take them to San Antonio, and they'd pass a test.

22:17.106 --> 22:20.891
And then when they'd, right here in Braddus 
County, they'd be sworn in. One time we swore in

22:20.971 --> 22:23.274
about 30 at one time. Wow. Old people, and they 
answered the question, and... They became

22:28.023 --> 22:32.408
citizens, and they were just thrilled to be able to 
vote, to have a voice in the government. And of

22:33.929 --> 22:39.976
course, the sons and daughters that were very 
proud of their parents because they were

22:33.929 --> 22:39.976
citizens. And so we did this. And that, I think, 
helped the community. And I was always very

22:48.845 --> 22:56.393
grateful to these lawyers that started this, that 
helped us. did not turn us down when we went to ask

22:56.558 --> 22:59.823
for their help. They did it pre-charge. They 
didn't charge anything. And they'd make several

23:02.827 --> 23:08.115
trips to see how we were doing to make sure that we 
were doing it right. And they liked what they saw.

23:10.739 --> 23:11.440
What about today? I think you've also been 
involved in some of this today. There's a lot of

23:14.004 --> 23:21.055
aliens that, with the recent amnesty program, 
also needed to verify it. Well, the only way I'm

23:21.095 --> 23:24.760
involved there, Peter, is that I'm able to write 
letters for them. You know, I write letters for

23:28.829 --> 23:44.109
them and also helpful fill out because when they go 
to this place where they're supposed to be

23:28.829 --> 23:44.109
processed, they'll give them a blank and say, you 
fill it or find somebody to fill it for you. Well,

23:44.550 --> 23:50.558
it's me they find or somebody like me and we fill 
these blanks based on what they tell us. And then we

23:51.559 --> 23:55.084
have a lot of this required notarization and some 
required letter attachment of some sort, and we do

23:55.587 --> 23:59.151
that. That's the only, that's the extent I'm 
involved in, but we do it, we don't charge anybody,

23:59.251 --> 24:05.699
we never charge anybody. We never have, you know. 
And so, and then anyway we can help them. Sometimes

24:12.747 --> 24:23.620
they have problems in Mexico, and, or somebody 
wants to go to Mexico, we write a letter on their

24:12.747 --> 24:23.620
behalf to the Immigration and Activation 
Service, and they'll give us what you call an

24:24.258 --> 24:28.603
emergency permit for them to go and come back. And 
that's the kind of thing we're involved in right

24:29.204 --> 24:31.147
now. Other than that, that's it. What about

24:33.870 --> 24:52.493
political action within the Hispanic community, 
specifically politicians that come from it, the

24:33.870 --> 24:52.493
way that local politicians have addressed the 
Hispanic community or tried to gain support from

24:33.870 --> 24:52.493
it? Can you comment on this, what it's been like? 
Well, unlike many years ago, the politicians

24:55.197 --> 25:08.378
today are really going after the Hispanic vote 
because there's so many of them here now. And

25:09.720 --> 25:19.476
because of that, the Hispanics are better off 
because

25:09.720 --> 25:19.476
they somehow or other, in certain areas, 
outnumber the Anglos and the blacks in some of

25:20.013 --> 25:26.560
these voting precincts.

25:29.303 --> 25:42.437
And when these officials get elected, they tend to 
remember that the Hispanic voted for them and they

25:29.303 --> 25:42.437
pass legislature that benefits Hispanic. But the 
Hispanic's been very active, too. If they see a

25:44.899 --> 25:49.564
candidate that that will serve the community well 
and will not forget them while they'll go out and

25:49.932 --> 26:02.272
stump for him and do what they can to help get him 
elected. But you don't see any of this, they're not

26:02.292 --> 26:09.203
after, they're not in for selfish purposes. They 
just want a good guy that is reasonable, that will

26:12.140 --> 26:16.565
understand, that will be somewhat sympathetic 
towards them. And that plot, that's it. That's all

26:18.247 --> 26:19.649
they want. And to me, I've been with these Aspani 
for so long. To me, the attitude is that if this guy

26:25.316 --> 26:31.803
does a good job this year, then I'll vote for him 
next time around. That's the extent of the

26:31.824 --> 26:34.226
interest in politics. That's it. Has this always 
been the case? To me, it's always been that way

